SCHEDULE I – MINIMUM FEATURES OF A RURAL EMPLOYMENT GUARANTEE SCHEME

1. The Scheme notified under section 4 by all States shall be called the Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee Scheme. All documents pertaining to the Scheme shall have a mention of the Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee Act, 2005.

3. Core objectives of the Scheme:
(a) Providing not less than one hundred days of unskilled manual work as a guaranteed employment in a financial year to every household in rural areas as per demand, resulting in creation of productive assets of prescribed quality and durability;
(b) Strengthening the livelihood resource base of the poor;
(c) Proactively ensuring social inclusion;
(d) Strengthening Panchayat Raj institutions.

4. CATEGORY A – PUBLIC WORKS RELATING TO NATURAL RESOURCES MANAGEMENT:
(i) Water conservation and water harvesting structures to augment and improve groundwater including underground dykes, earthen dams, stop dams, check dams;
(ii) Watershed management works such as contour trenches, terracing, contour bunds, boulder checks, gabion structures and spring shed development;
(iii) Micro and minor irrigation works and creation, renovation and maintenance of irrigation canals and drains;
(iv) Renovation of traditional water bodies including desilting of irrigation tanks and conservation of old step wells or baolis;
(v) Afforestation, tree plantation and horticulture in common and forest lands, road margins, canal bunds, tank foreshores and coastal belts;
(vi) Land development works in common land.

CATEGORY B – COMMUNITY ASSETS OR INDIVIDUAL ASSETS FOR VULNERABLE SECTIONS (only for households in Paragraph 5):
(i) Improving productivity of lands through land development and suitable infrastructure for irrigation including dug wells, farm ponds;
(ii) Improving livelihoods through horticulture, sericulture, plantation, and farm forestry;
(iii) Development of fallow or waste lands to bring under cultivation;
(iv) Unskilled wage component in construction of houses sanctioned under Indira Awaas Yojana or other State or Central Government Schemes;
(v) Creating infrastructure for promotion of livestock (poultry, goat, piggery, cattle shelters and fodder troughs);
(vi) Creating infrastructure for promotion of fisheries (fish drying yards, storage facilities, promotion of fisheries in seasonal water bodies on public land).

5. Works creating individual assets shall be prioritised on land or homestead owned by households belonging to: Scheduled Castes; Scheduled Tribes; nomadic tribes; denotified tribes; other families below the poverty line; women-headed households; physically handicapped headed households; beneficiaries of land reforms; beneficiaries under Indira Awaas Yojana; beneficiaries under the Scheduled Tribes and Other Traditional Forest Dwellers (Recognition of Forest Rights) Act, 2006; and small or marginal farmers.

CATEGORY C – COMMON INFRASTRUCTURE INCLUDING FOR NRLM COMPLIANT SELF HELP GROUPS:
(i) Works for promoting agricultural productivity by creating durable infrastructure required for bio-fertilizers and post-harvest facilities including pucca storage facilities;
(ii) Common work-sheds for livelihood activities of self-help groups.

CATEGORY D – RURAL INFRASTRUCTURE:
(i) Rural sanitation related works — individual household latrines, school toilet units, Anganwadi toilets, and solid and liquid waste management;
(ii) Providing all-weather rural road connectivity to unconnected villages and construction of pucca internal roads or streets including side drains and culverts within a village;
(iii) Construction of play fields and compound walls for Government run schools in villages;
(iv) Works for improving disaster preparedness or restoration of roads, flood control and protection works, drainage in water logged areas, deepening and repairing of flood channels;
(v) Construction of buildings for Gram Panchayats, women self-help groups' federations, cyclone shelters, Anganwadi centres, village haats and crematoria;
(vi) Construction of Food Grain Storage Structures;
(vii) Production of building material required for construction works under the Act;
(viii) Maintenance of rural public assets created under the Act;
(ix) Any other work notified by the Central Government in consultation with the State.

At least 60% of the works to be taken up in a district in terms of cost shall be for creation of productive assets directly linked to agriculture and allied activities.

6. The State Government shall take concrete steps to achieve effective inter-departhental convergence to improve the quality and productivity of assets.

7. There shall be a systematic, participatory planning exercise at each tier of Panchayat, conducted between August to December every year.

8. Demand for work, either oral or written, shall be registered as and when required by any job card holder and in the Rozgar Diwas conducted at every Ward and Gram Panchayat level at least once a month.

9. Adequate shelf of works shall be maintained by every Gram Panchayat to meet the expected demand for work. At least one labour intensive public work with at least one work suitable for Particularly Vulnerable Groups (especially the aged and disabled) shall be kept open at all times.

11. Work shall be provided within fifteen days from the date of registration of the demand for work.

13. Every work under the Scheme shall have a technical estimate duly sanctioned by an authority authorised by the State Government.

14. Administrative or financial sanction shall be given by the competent authority within thirty days from the date of finalisation of the works at the Gram Panchayat level.

15. Muster rolls for works under the Scheme:
(a) Each muster roll shall be in English or local language and have a unique identity number electronically generated by the computer system (e-Muster). Every muster roll shall be signed by the authorised person of the Gram Panchayat or by the Programme Officer;
(b) Muster rolls shall be maintained at the worksite with daily attendance; details shall be made available in public view on a daily basis using the computer system;
(d) The muster roll shall be closed on the last given day, counter-signed by every worker who has worked, and handed over to the technical personnel for measurement;
(g) Any person shall have access to muster rolls on the worksite on demand during working hours.

16. Payment shall only be made based on the measurements taken at the worksite by authorised personnel within three days of closure of the muster roll.

17. The State Government shall link the wages, without any gender bias, with the quantity of work done and it shall be paid according to the rural schedule of rates.

18. A separate Schedule of rates shall be finalised for women, the elderly, people with disabilities and people with debilitating ailments to improve their participation.

19. The schedule of rates shall be fixed so that an adult person working for eight hours (including an hour of rest) will earn a wage equal to the stipulated wage rate. Working hours shall be flexible but shall not spread over more than twelve hours on any day.

20. For all works, the cost of the material component including wages of skilled and semi-skilled workers shall not exceed forty percent at the district level.

21. Works shall be executed without engaging any contractor.

22. As far as practicable, works shall be performed using manual labour and no labour displacing machines shall be used.

23. All material required for works shall be procured by the Gram Panchayat or implementing agency using a transparent tender process.

25. Transparency and accountability provisions include:
(1) Display at each worksite the 'Janata' estimate showing details of the work, estimated labour days, quantities of materials;
(2) Display on prominent walls or public boards in the village: job cards list, number of days of work provided and wages paid;
(3) Display through boards at the Gram Panchayat Office: shelf of projects approved, employment provided, funds received and expenditure;
(4) Display on the website: all information shall be available in public domain through free downloadable electronic form.

25(b) Concurrent social audit shall be done for all works every month.

25(c) Social audit: Implementation of all conditions for guaranteed rural employment shall be subjected to social audit at least once in every six months:
(i) Identification and training of local youth as social auditors; formation of trained social auditor teams for each Gram Panchayat with youth from outside the Gram Panchayat; at least 25% of village social auditors shall be from SC/ST groups;
(ii) Provision of records (muster rolls, M-Books, pay orders) to social audit teams free of cost;
(iii) Verification of every worksite to cross-check measurements;
(iv) Verification of every disbursement with concerned beneficiaries;
(ix) Systematic follow-up action on social audit reports; completing recovery of amounts found misappropriated within 6 months.

29. Effective grievance redressal mechanism:
(a) Institutional mechanisms for receiving grievances, with one day each week for receiving grievances at Ward/GP/Block and District level;
(b) Issuance of dated receipt to complaints;
(c) Enquiry and disposal to be completed within 7 working days;
(d) Grievance to be redressed within 15 days;
(e) Failure to dispose of a complaint within seven days shall be considered a contravention under section 25;
(i) Appeals: against Gram Panchayat orders → Programme Officer; against Programme Officer → District Programme Coordinator; against District Programme Coordinator → State Commissioner (NREGS); all appeals to be made within 45 days and disposed within one month.

30. Ombudsperson: There shall be an Ombudsperson for each District for receiving grievances, enquiring into and passing awards as per guidelines issued.

34. All accounts and records including muster rolls relating to the Scheme shall be made available for public scrutiny free of cost. Copies may be provided on demand not later than three working days.

35. There shall be a Capacity Building Plan, Information Education Communication plan and a plan for strengthening Panchayats as a part of the Scheme.

THE NATIONAL RURAL EMPLOYMENT GUARANTEE (CENTRAL COUNCIL) RULES, 2006

Rule 1 – Short title and commencement: These rules may be called the National Rural Employment Guarantee (Central Council) Rules, 2006. They came into force on 25-5-2006.

Rule 3 – The Central Council: The Central Council shall consist of:
(a) Union Minister for Rural Development — Chairperson, ex officio;
(b) Secretaries/nominees from Ministries of Rural Development, Women and Child Development, Agriculture, Environment and Forest, Statistics and Programme Implementation, Panchayat Raj, Tribal Affairs, Social Justice and Empowerment; one representative each from Planning Commission, Prime Minister's Office, Ministry of Law and Justice, Ministry of Labour and Employment (all at Joint Secretary level or above);
(c) Six representatives of State Government departhents of rural development (not below rank of Secretary) nominated by the Central Government;
(d) Twelve members from Panchayati Raj Institutions, organisations of workers and disadvantaged groups — four shall be women; includes two from Scheduled Castes, one each from Scheduled Tribes, Other Backward Classes and minorities; and two chairpersons of District Panchayats nominated by rotation for one year;
(e) Eight members representing the States — one expert each in: works (water conservation, land development, afforestation), social audit, wage employment, print/electronic media, climate change, convergence, law, and communication/information technology;
(f) Joint Secretary in charge of NREGA as Member-Secretary.

Rule 4 – Terms and conditions of appointhent:
Official members from Ministries hold office as long as they serve in their respective Ministries. State Government representatives hold office for one year. Non-official members hold office for one year at a time and are eligible for re-nomination, but no person shall hold office for more than three years in any case.

Rule 5 – Resignation and removal of non-official members:
A non-official member may be removed if he has been adjudged an insolvent; convicted of an offence involving moral turpitude; become physically or mentally incapable; acquired financial or other interest likely to affect prejudicially his functions; or remains absent for three consecutive meetings without permission.
